A nested "try-catch" block, also known as a try-catch-finally block within another try block, is a construct in which you have a "try" block inside another "try" block. This is often used when you want to handle exceptions at different levels of a program, or when you want to catch and handle specific exceptions at different points in your code.

The syntax for a nested try-catch block in Java looks like this:

```java
try {
    // Outer try block
    // Code that may potentially throw exceptions
    try {
        // Inner try block
        // Code that may potentially throw exceptions
    } catch (ExceptionType1 e1) {
        // Handle ExceptionType1 within the inner catch block
    }
} catch (ExceptionType2 e2) {
    // Handle ExceptionType2 within the outer catch block
} finally {
    // Code that will be executed whether or not an exception is thrown
}
```

Here's how it works:

1. The code inside the outer "try" block is executed.
2. If an exception is thrown within the outer "try" block, the program will jump to the appropriate "catch" block based on the type of exception, if there is one that matches.
3. If no matching exception is found in the outer "catch" block, the program will jump to the inner "try" block.
4. If an exception is thrown within the inner "try" block, the program will jump to the corresponding "catch" block within the inner "try-catch" block.
5. If there are no matching exceptions in the inner "catch" block, the exception will propagate to the outer "catch" block.
6. The "finally" block, whether inside the inner or outer "try-catch" blocks, will always be executed, regardless of whether an exception occurred.

Using nested try-catch blocks can help you handle exceptions at multiple levels of your program, making your error-handling logic more robust and specific to different parts of your code.

